<hr width="75%"><B>Comments:</B><BR>
<INPUT TYPE="hidden" value="Taib Bershain 4/5/00 This bug is due to the predictive tracking done by the AI to compensate for a moving target. It attempts to calculate if the object in question continues on it's present course at it's present speed, where will it be? It then releases the object and sends it to that point, being that it will likely be behind you if the monster is now close, it reads as striking you. This is especially true in spell casters, as spells are MUCH slower than arrows, and some fast monsters CANNOT be hit if they have decided to move at all from their static location, or are not in one place.<BR>">Taib Bershain 4/5/00 This bug is due to the predictive tracking done by the AI to compensate for a moving target. It attempts to calculate if the object in question continues on it's present course at it's present speed, where will it be? It then releases the object and sends it to that point, being that it will likely be behind you if the monster is now close, it reads as striking you. This is especially true in spell casters, as spells are MUCH slower than arrows, and some fast monsters CANNOT be hit if they have decided to move at all from their static location, or are not in one place.<BR>
